1
00:00:14,053 --> 00:00:18,071
For www.forom.com

2
00:01:45,868 --> 00:01:48,834
<i>Previously on "Dexter"...

3
00:01:49,067 --> 00:01:50,900
<i>Tonight's the night.

4
00:01:50,933 --> 00:01:53,967
<i>And it's going to happen
again and again -

5
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:56,367
<i>Has to happen.

6
00:01:56,401 --> 00:02:00,134
<i>There he is.
He's the one.

7
00:02:02,734 --> 00:02:05,768
You're mine now,
so do exactly as I say.

8
00:02:05,833 --> 00:02:07,634
You better be a cop.

9
00:02:07,645 --> 00:02:08,630
No...
Forensics.

10
00:02:08,676 --> 00:02:10,460
There is no blood
near the body at all.

11
00:02:10,503 --> 00:02:12,365
It's the weirdest thing
you ever saw.

12
00:02:12,380 --> 00:02:16,737
<i>I've never seen such clean,
dry, neat-Looking dead flesh.

13
00:02:16,761 --> 00:02:18,767
How is he doing? How does the
killer get rid of the blood?

14
00:02:18,809 --> 00:02:20,452
One of these days,
you're gonna tell me.

15
00:02:20,467 --> 00:02:23,303
I told you blood spatter
doesn't take up all my time.

16
00:02:23,336 --> 00:02:25,330
How the hell was your date
with Rita last night?

17
00:02:25,368 --> 00:02:26,230
Great.

18
00:02:26,268 --> 00:02:27,982
<i>She's perfect because Rita is,

19
00:02:27,996 --> 00:02:30,632
<i>in her own way,
as damaged as me.

20
00:02:30,666 --> 00:02:33,602
Open your eyes
and look at what you did!

21
00:02:33,636 --> 00:02:35,262
Please,
you have to understand.

22
00:02:35,306 --> 00:02:37,800
Trust me.
I definitely understand.

23
00:02:41,365 --> 00:02:42,581
Hello?

24
00:02:42,606 --> 00:02:43,842
What are you doing now?

25
00:02:43,907 --> 00:02:46,831
I'm just finishing up a little
project, but I'll come by later.

26
00:02:46,868 --> 00:02:48,433
- They found another hooker.
- Une autre ?

27
00:02:48,467 --> 00:02:50,363
That's the third one
in five months.

28
00:02:50,386 --> 00:02:52,002
Third?
You mean there's a...

29
00:02:52,026 --> 00:02:53,302
Serial killer, that's right.

30
00:02:53,367 --> 00:02:56,331
Dex, there are people out there
who do really bad things.

31
00:02:56,365 --> 00:02:57,713
Of course, you have to
learn how to spot them,

32
00:02:57,735 --> 00:02:59,263
but I can teach you.

33
00:02:59,408 --> 00:03:03,062
The killer flayed the skin,
the flesh, completely off.

34
00:03:03,106 --> 00:03:04,132
Why would he do that?

35
00:03:04,168 --> 00:03:05,330
He's experimenting,

36
00:03:05,378 --> 00:03:06,862
Trying to find the right way.

37
00:03:06,908 --> 00:03:09,482
<i>He's certainly raising the bar.
Damn!

38
00:03:09,987 --> 00:03:11,763
<i>This guy is good.

39
00:03:11,786 --> 00:03:13,103
The killer is an artist.

40
00:03:13,136 --> 00:03:15,101
You give me the fucking creeps.
You know that, Dexter?

41
00:03:15,135 --> 00:03:17,251
Yeah, I know.
Sorry about that.

42
00:03:17,306 --> 00:03:18,880
But now we have a fourth body,

43
00:03:18,897 --> 00:03:20,461
and the cuts were different.

44
00:03:20,485 --> 00:03:21,840
And that's tellings a story.

45
00:03:21,857 --> 00:03:23,403
The ritual is changing.

46
00:03:23,437 --> 00:03:24,551
I'd like to check and see

47
00:03:24,586 --> 00:03:25,981
if any refrigerated trucks

48
00:03:26,006 --> 00:03:28,530
have been stolen
in the last week or so.

49
00:03:31,536 --> 00:03:32,940
It just seems odd.

50
00:03:33,008 --> 00:03:35,001
Your sister has
this ice-truck theory,

51
00:03:35,056 --> 00:03:37,402
and then here you are
to back it up.

52
00:03:37,436 --> 00:03:40,061
She's good, lieutenant.
You should give her a chance.

53
00:03:41,337 --> 00:03:43,231
<i>I think this is a friendly message.

54
00:03:43,268 --> 00:03:45,330
<i>"Hey, want to play?"

55
00:03:45,367 --> 00:03:47,463
<i>And, yes, I want to play.

56
00:03:47,665 --> 00:03:49,563
<i>I really, really do.

57
00:04:10,905 --> 00:04:12,461
<i>I dream.

58
00:04:15,705 --> 00:04:20,302
<i>I dream I'm floating
on the surface of my own life,

59
00:04:20,338 --> 00:04:24,730
<i>watching it unfold,
observing it.

60
00:04:24,768 --> 00:04:28,432
<i>I'm the outsider, looking in.

61
00:04:38,408 --> 00:04:40,330
Yeah! Man!

62
00:04:40,365 --> 00:04:43,401
You want to play, man?!
Come on!

63
00:04:43,435 --> 00:04:45,061
In the water!

64
00:04:47,155 --> 00:04:49,963
<i>Look at them.
They can laugh and play.

65
00:04:50,036 --> 00:04:52,433
<i>It comes so easily for them.

66
00:04:54,706 --> 00:04:57,262
<i>Even though
I'm not one of them,

67
00:04:57,307 --> 00:05:00,122
<i>even though sometimes
I can really be a monster...

68
00:05:01,566 --> 00:05:03,963
<i>today, I'm just...

69
00:05:04,008 --> 00:05:06,430
<i>...a sea monster.

70
00:05:23,538 --> 00:05:26,920
<i>Soon enough, I'll have to go
back to doing what I do...

71
00:05:27,567 --> 00:05:32,062
<i>So I make a point of enjoying
days like this when I have them.

72
00:05:46,807 --> 00:05:48,332
Just a second.

73
00:05:49,177 --> 00:05:52,763
<i>The ice-truck killer left me
a gruesome souvenir.

74
00:05:53,105 --> 00:05:56,102
<i>Explaining it
could be kind of...

75
00:05:56,438 --> 00:05:57,602
< i>...awkward.

76
00:05:59,036 --> 00:06:00,332
Hey.

77
00:06:00,347 --> 00:06:02,101
Bagels, brother.
Let me in.

78
00:06:08,405 --> 00:06:10,762
Could it be more
depressing in here?

79
00:06:12,566 --> 00:06:14,863
Got anything to drink?
It's hot as hell out there.

80
00:06:14,907 --> 00:06:16,231
O.J.?

81
00:06:16,365 --> 00:06:18,030
With ice.

82
00:06:22,607 --> 00:06:24,231
So, how you doing?

83
00:06:24,266 --> 00:06:25,563
I'm fine.

84
00:06:25,586 --> 00:06:27,323
Yeah, things are fine.

85
00:06:27,335 --> 00:06:29,760
Breakfast, which I already had,
was fine, but...

86
00:06:29,806 --> 00:06:31,833
you know me...
I'm always hungry.

87
00:06:38,668 --> 00:06:40,302
So, what's up, hotshot?

88
00:06:40,336 --> 00:06:41,830
All right, get this...

89
00:06:41,865 --> 00:06:45,552
Lieutenant's looking
for that refrigerated truck

90
00:06:45,577 --> 00:06:48,030
in every swamp, glade, and chop shop
from here to the Keys.

91
00:06:48,065 --> 00:06:49,731
But the way I see it,

92
00:06:50,367 --> 00:06:54,630
that whackjob truck driver threw
a severed head at your car.

93
00:06:54,668 --> 00:06:56,232
It's not as if he's shy.

94
00:06:56,265 --> 00:06:58,202
You think he's hiding the truck
in plain sight,

95
00:06:58,237 --> 00:06:59,353
wanting it to be found?

96
00:06:59,378 --> 00:07:01,571
I could answer that if Laguerta
didn't have me back with my hookers,

97
00:07:01,578 --> 00:07:03,130
looking for a witness...

98
00:07:03,158 --> 00:07:05,691
Finding that truck is your
golden ticket into Homicide.

99
00:07:05,706 --> 00:07:06,603
Tell me about it.

100
00:07:06,616 --> 00:07:09,232
Just because Laguerta has you
looking for hookers on her time

101
00:07:09,246 --> 00:07:10,581
doesn't mean you can't look
for the truck...

102
00:07:10,598 --> 00:07:11,942
...On my time!

103
00:07:12,708 --> 00:07:15,330
What's with these?

104
00:07:15,368 --> 00:07:17,062
I've got court.

105
00:07:19,236 --> 00:07:22,401
Why is it we never talk
brother-sister stuff?

106
00:07:23,015 --> 00:07:25,673
Our dad was a cop. You're a cop.
I work for the cops.

107
00:07:25,707 --> 00:07:27,832
For us, this is
brother-sister stuff.

108
00:07:29,645 --> 00:07:31,503
Brings out your eyes.

109
00:07:36,667 --> 00:07:39,333
<i>First he throws
a severed head at me,

110
00:07:39,367 --> 00:07:41,932
<i>then he leaves me
these doll parts,

111
00:07:41,967 --> 00:07:44,261
<i>like pieces of a puzzle.

112
00:07:44,308 --> 00:07:46,032
<i>I like puzzles.

113
00:07:53,467 --> 00:07:57,201
<i>But there's nothing more frustrating than
putting a puzzle together and finding then

114
00:07:57,988 --> 00:08:01,001
<i>it still doesn't make sense.

115
00:08:05,406 --> 00:08:08,032
Please state
your name and occupation.

116
00:08:08,065 --> 00:08:11,431
My name is Dexter Morgan,
and I'm a forensics specialist

117
00:08:11,465 --> 00:08:13,033
in blood-spatter analysis

118
00:08:13,067 --> 00:08:14,863
for the Miami metro
police department.

119
00:08:14,906 --> 00:08:17,802
And how long have you been
doing blood-spatter analysis?

120
00:08:17,837 --> 00:08:19,261
Almost twelve years.

121
00:08:19,308 --> 00:08:21,462
You've been involved
in quite a few cases, then.

122
00:08:21,508 --> 00:08:23,632
2,103.

123
00:08:23,667 --> 00:08:25,663
Give or take.

124
00:08:25,706 --> 00:08:28,061
No, 2,103.

125
00:08:28,607 --> 00:08:32,182
Then it's safe to say
blood is your life.

126
00:08:33,767 --> 00:08:35,673
Safe to say.

127
00:08:35,705 --> 00:08:39,461
<i>Unlike the other guys down at the station,
I love coming to court to rub shoulders

128
00:08:39,507 --> 00:08:42,171
<i>with the good people
of the Sunshine State...

129
00:08:42,435 --> 00:08:44,831
<i>...and Sasquatch.

130
00:08:44,967 --> 00:08:47,983
<i>In a courthouse, everyone's
on their best behavior...

131
00:08:51,436 --> 00:08:53,602
<i>...like they're being watched.

132
00:08:58,166 --> 00:09:00,160
<i>And they are.

133
00:09:00,207 --> 00:09:01,751
<i>Some people would look
at this family

134
00:09:01,766 --> 00:09:04,031
<i>and see only tragedy
and heartbreak.

135
00:09:04,166 --> 00:09:06,500
<i>But I see so much more
than that.

136
00:09:06,518 --> 00:09:10,001
I'll do this, okay?

137
00:09:12,006 --> 00:09:14,682
<i>I see opportunity.

138
00:09:16,635 --> 00:09:18,862
Alexander Pryce finished
his homework,

139
00:09:18,897 --> 00:09:21,752
kissed his mom,
went out for a jog.

140
00:09:21,765 --> 00:09:24,232
He told her he'd be back in time
to take out the trash cans.

141
00:09:24,268 --> 00:09:27,461
Just another night,
until...

142
00:09:28,378 --> 00:09:30,530
...until the defendant
not only struck him

143
00:09:30,555 --> 00:09:32,380
with his car but fled the scene,

144
00:09:32,403 --> 00:09:35,905
leaving Alexander Pryce
alone and dying for hours

145
00:09:35,930 --> 00:09:37,967
before his body was found
the next morning...

146
00:09:38,401 --> 00:09:42,307
From heinous to unspeakable.

147
00:09:42,339 --> 00:09:44,872
The people will prove that
not only did Mr. Chambers

148
00:09:44,895 --> 00:09:46,800
strike and kill Alexander Pryce

149
00:09:46,838 --> 00:09:50,232
but did so while once again
under the influence of alcohol.

150
00:09:51,517 --> 00:09:53,513
Happy birthday, Alex!

151
00:09:53,737 --> 00:09:55,133
Thank you.

152
00:09:55,165 --> 00:09:56,591
- Rip right into it.
- What?

153
00:09:56,768 --> 00:09:59,162
- Yeah.
- Hope it's money.

154
00:09:59,206 --> 00:10:00,663
Yeah, you wish.

155
00:10:00,866 --> 00:10:01,832
Surprise.

156
00:10:01,938 --> 00:10:04,400
Thanks, guys.
It's like 80 degrees out.

157
00:10:04,437 --> 00:10:06,333
But next year
at this time,

158
00:10:06,367 --> 00:10:09,202
we're coming to visit you
at Harvard.

159
00:10:09,238 --> 00:10:12,763
It's everything I've ever
wanted for you, Alexander.

160
00:10:12,808 --> 00:10:14,001
Thanks, dad.

161
00:10:14,038 --> 00:10:16,830
All right, enough corniness.

162
00:10:17,706 --> 00:10:19,702
<i>I see their pain.

163
00:10:20,135 --> 00:10:23,451
<i>On some level,
I even understand their pain.

164
00:10:24,106 --> 00:10:26,623
<i>I just can't feel their pain.

165
00:10:31,666 --> 00:10:34,090
<i>It just a Matter of time
before we see how far

166
00:10:34,108 --> 00:10:37,361
<i>Matt Chambers's crocodile tears
will get him.

167
00:10:39,135 --> 00:10:41,263
<i>But until then,

168
00:10:42,006 --> 00:10:45,142
<i>a little of my favorite
tropical fruit...

169
00:10:46,268 --> 00:10:49,903
<i>The perfect driving food
next to a pulled-pork sandwich.

170
00:10:50,236 --> 00:10:52,932
<i>Also, I can keep my energy up
for the day job.

171
00:10:52,966 --> 00:10:55,800
* ven conmigo... *

172
00:11:02,137 --> 00:11:08,130
* junto a mi corazón *

173
00:11:08,756 --> 00:11:12,362
* y me quite la vida*

174
00:11:12,547 --> 00:11:17,581
*si no tengo tu amor *

175
00:11:23,207 --> 00:11:24,203
Detective!

176
00:11:24,217 --> 00:11:25,933
- Buena.
- Buena?

177
00:11:26,237 --> 00:11:27,132
Did we get an I.D.?

178
00:11:27,148 --> 00:11:28,811
First on scene pulled the wallet.

179
00:11:28,848 --> 00:11:30,092
We're still waiting.

180
00:11:30,137 --> 00:11:31,462
Hello, Dex.

181
00:11:31,708 --> 00:11:34,663
<i>Her boss -
Lieutenant Laguerta.

182
00:11:34,705 --> 00:11:36,703
<i>In keeping with her total sense
of entitlement,

183
00:11:36,728 --> 00:11:39,360
<i>she has this attraction to me.

184
00:11:39,806 --> 00:11:41,880
<i>And I thought I was creepy.

185
00:11:43,165 --> 00:11:45,372
Given the skin rupture
and the secondary spatter,

186
00:11:45,435 --> 00:11:48,031
distance had to be
a 50-, 60-foot drop.

187
00:11:48,067 --> 00:11:50,333
The eastbound's only 40 feet.

188
00:11:50,365 --> 00:11:52,811
It's not high enough
for this kind of damage so...

189
00:11:52,815 --> 00:11:56,132
...best guess, originating point
is the westbound causeway.

190
00:11:57,965 --> 00:12:01,061
Get me a team
on the westbound causeway!

191
00:12:01,088 --> 00:12:02,633
She's good.

192
00:12:02,667 --> 00:12:04,120
Angel, look at this.

193
00:12:06,467 --> 00:12:08,710
I think there's something
in his mouth.

194
00:12:11,206 --> 00:12:12,231
Medic!

195
00:12:19,136 --> 00:12:21,562
It's just a death rattle.
He's gonzo.

196
00:12:21,587 --> 00:12:23,422
You better check
out my friend, too.

197
00:12:23,436 --> 00:12:25,363
No telling what this guy
might have had.

198
00:12:29,037 --> 00:12:31,533
This is what he had.

199
00:12:33,336 --> 00:12:36,263
Call me crazy, Angel,
but I think this is human flesh.

200
00:13:03,966 --> 00:13:06,602
Hooked up
with Sean last night.

201
00:13:07,606 --> 00:13:09,061
The cable-guy Sean?

202
00:13:09,106 --> 00:13:10,631
God, no.

203
00:13:10,665 --> 00:13:12,200
He smelled like cheese.

204
00:13:12,238 --> 00:13:14,160
So the mechanic Sean?

205
00:13:14,208 --> 00:13:15,662
Yep.

206
00:13:15,908 --> 00:13:17,661
He came over.

207
00:13:17,708 --> 00:13:20,430
We opened a bottle
of Pinot gris.

208
00:13:20,468 --> 00:13:22,461
We finished a bottle
of Pinot gris.

209
00:13:22,508 --> 00:13:24,200
Before I knew it,
we were...

210
00:13:24,236 --> 00:13:26,002
Stop that.

211
00:13:26,038 --> 00:13:27,801
You don't want
to hear this, do you?

212
00:13:27,837 --> 00:13:29,202
No.

213
00:13:29,235 --> 00:13:32,230
But if you two are getting
serious, I'd love to meet him.

214
00:13:32,266 --> 00:13:33,763
Why don't you
and Sean the mechanic

215
00:13:33,768 --> 00:13:36,951
join me and Rita the girlfriend
for dinner tomorrow night?

216
00:13:36,975 --> 00:13:38,053
Why?

217
00:13:38,086 --> 00:13:40,491
So you can tell me later he's not
good enough for your little sister?

218
00:13:40,517 --> 00:13:41,301
Don't.

219
00:13:41,316 --> 00:13:44,282
You're the one who was going on about
brother-and-sister stuff this morning.

220
00:13:44,297 --> 00:13:46,903
And that becomes
brother-and-sister double-dating?

221
00:13:46,907 --> 00:13:48,350
Because I'm on head of yours.

222
00:13:48,376 --> 00:13:50,000
Come on.
It'll be fun.

223
00:13:50,005 --> 00:13:52,991
All right, we'll go, but I'm not
promising we'll have any fun.

224
00:13:53,555 --> 00:13:54,563
Not now.

225
00:13:55,307 --> 00:13:57,100
What crawled up his ass?

226
00:13:57,135 --> 00:13:58,903
He hates lab rats.

227
00:13:58,936 --> 00:14:00,932
Well, here's a headline...

228
00:14:00,968 --> 00:14:04,261
It's lab rats that make
us cops look good.

229
00:14:05,307 --> 00:14:07,142
Okay, listen up.

230
00:14:07,247 --> 00:14:10,650
We just got an I.D. on the body
from under the causeway.

231
00:14:10,695 --> 00:14:12,321
His name is Ricky Simmons.

232
00:14:12,936 --> 00:14:15,001
He was a cop.

233
00:14:31,605 --> 00:14:33,861
- Let me ask you something.
- Yeah.

234
00:14:34,068 --> 00:14:37,202
When we were partners, you used
to use every excuse in the book

235
00:14:37,235 --> 00:14:39,401
to get out of making
a next-of-kin notification.

236
00:14:39,437 --> 00:14:41,900
I knew Ricky from
the department softball team.

237
00:14:41,937 --> 00:14:44,833
He was a good guy, a good cop.
It's the least I could do.

238
00:14:53,467 --> 00:14:54,630
Motherfucker!

239
00:14:58,965 --> 00:15:00,500
Call it in!

240
00:15:03,008 --> 00:15:05,031
3H-77 to dispatch.

241
00:15:05,768 --> 00:15:08,403
We need E.M.T.
and police backup now.

242
00:15:08,558 --> 00:15:09,971
I'll check the house.

243
00:15:09,978 --> 00:15:12,230
Kara, it's me.
It's James.

244
00:15:12,265 --> 00:15:14,160
You're okay.

245
00:15:16,668 --> 00:15:19,802
It's me.

246
00:15:19,836 --> 00:15:22,012
It's okay.

247
00:15:22,605 --> 00:15:25,602
This is so fucked-up, man.

248
00:15:28,568 --> 00:15:31,030
Going after a cop's family...

249
00:15:31,168 --> 00:15:32,920
Who would do such a thing?

250
00:15:33,007 --> 00:15:34,641
That's why we're here.

251
00:15:35,535 --> 00:15:37,260
But it's still fucked-up.

252
00:15:37,305 --> 00:15:41,173
They're telling me Ricky Simmons was under
deep cover in Carlos Guerrero's family.

253
00:15:41,766 --> 00:15:43,500
All right.
Thanks.

254
